21_0	0.14863465	WASHINGTON (AP) --Obese women are six times more likely than thin women to have a silent, smoldering inflammation inside their arteries that may increase their already high risk of developing heart disease, researchers said Tuesday.
21_1	0.14800337	If the findings are verified, they suggest scientists should study whether the aspirin some heart patients take might also help overweight people reduce their chances of heart attacks.
21_2	0.16857355	Being overweight is an automatic warning sign for heart disease: The fatter people are, the more likely they are to have high cholesterol and clogged arteries, high blood pressure, diabetes and other cardiovascular risk factors.
21_3	0.070968272	But no one knew if those extra pounds could cause yet another risk: low-grade inflammation inside a person's arteries.
21_4	0.1020265	In otherwise seemingly healthy people, scientists recently discovered that this low-grade inflammation can simmer for years and significantly increase a person's risk of a heart attack or stroke.
21_5	0.054470638	No one knows what causes the subtle inflammation.
21_6	0.095741731	One theory has been that it might be bacteria, and indeed, some research suggests that antibiotics may help fight heart disease.
21_7	0.085779537	On the other hand, doctors already frequently prescribe aspirin to certain people at high risk of heart attacks because it thins their blood --and aspirin also reduces inflammation.
21_8	0.089392162	Dutch scientist Marjolein Visser knew that fat cells themselves can produce a substance called interleukin-6 that causes inflammation when it seeps into the bloodstream.
21_9	0.089243148	So she studied whether obesity could be another culprit, using a U.S. database of 16,000 Americans.
21_10	0.07615187	The only way to measure this ``micro-inflammation'' is using a blood test that detects C-reactive protein, or CRP.
21_11	0.09966247	CRP levels skyrocket when people are sick, with colds, inflammatory diseases like rheumatoid arthritis, even heart disease.
21_12	0.082307913	But lower levels, between 0.2 milligrams and 1 mg per deciliter of blood, are the ones that signal the simmering inflammation that has scientists concerned.
21_13	0.12271532	Visser discovered that obese women are six times more likely to have this low-grade inflammation than normal-weight people.
21_14	0.13599823	Obese men were twice as likely to have it, a gender difference Visser couldn't explain, except to say that women in the study were much more overweight than men studied.
21_15	0.093619368	``We were surprised'' the risk was so high, Visser said Tuesday, before presenting her findings at a biology meeting here.
21_16	0.091261087	If verified, ``it could have quite an impact''.
21_17	0.093899412	Visser, a weight specialist at Amsterdam's Vrije University, statistically controlled for other diseases that might have caused the study participants' CRP levels to rise.
21_18	0.1033407	She found equal risk when examining only healthy people under age 40.
21_19	0.097193828	Even ``at a young age, when you're obese there's this inflammation, and we know it's bad for you,'' she said.
21_20	0.14858842	The study isn't proof that obesity inflames people's arteries, cautioned Dr.
21_21	0.046501483	Richard J.
21_22	0.15605929	Havlik of the National Institute on Aging, which funded the research.
21_23	0.092281596	But the federal agency is intrigued enough that it is funding more research into the link --and probing whether obesity-caused inflammation might have ramifications for other diseases, too.
21_24	0.087200919	First, Visser is preparing to see whether losing weight causes CRP levels to drop immediately.
21_25	0.094388625	Her findings, however, raise the question of whether aspirin or any of the dozens of other anti-inflammatory drugs, like ibuprofen, could help obese people ward off heart disease, and she cautions that nobody has tested that yet.
21_26	0.092280495	``The best thing to do if you're obese is lose weight instead of hitting the aspirin bottle,'' she cautioned.
